<chapter>

name = Full Properties Documentation
subtitle = Avoiding assignment errors

<text>

By now, you should know that there are three types of main, top-level nodes. (By the way, $<nodes> and $<subnodes> will be signified with a pair of greater than and less than symbols $(<>) from now on.) The types are the $<global> node, the $<character> node, and the $<chapter> node. If you misplace property assignments, the values will either be ignored or used for the wrong purpose.

(break)

Furthermore, DDTXTs are not like XML files. You can only have two layers of nodes at any time and they must follow one of these.

(break)

The following is a complete list of all document properties and where they should be placed. These tables are in the following format:
[note: Property #= Type of input | Description of purpose | Default value]
(divide)

[note: $<global> node]

$<global> have two kinds of $<subnodes>: $<style> and $<text>. The main $<global> node itself has four properties. Original explanation: [href: ##chapter-3]
(break)
name #= word(s) | Full document name | Untitled DDTXT
(break)
author #= word(s) | Document author(s) | Unknown Author
(break)
webtitle #= | Abbreviated document name shown in tab and top statistics bar | Full document name
(break)
provideTableOfContents #= true/false | "true" generates a table of contents based on chapter names and order. This manual has this set to "true". | "false"

(break)

(horizon)

[note: $<global> $<style> subnode]

The $<global> $<style> subnode has the following properties. Original explanation: [href: ##chapter-14].
(break)
color #= CSS color | Main text color | "black"
(break)
backgroundColor #= CSS color | Background color | "white"
(break)
headingColor #= CSS color | Color of chapter titles and subtitles | "inherit" ("black")
(break)
titleColor #= CSS color | Color of document title | "inherit" ("black")
(break)
divide #= word(s) | Text used for document divisions. Use (left parenthesis)break) or (left parenthesis)horizon) to add extra space or borders. | $"~~~"
(break)
divideColor #= CSS color | Color of division text | "inherit" ("black")
(break)
divideSize #= Npx, where "N" is a number | Size, in pixels, of font used for division text | "50px"
(break)
break #= $"<br>", repeated as many times as you need to get the spacing you want | What amount of space to insert in (left parenthesis)break)s. The default is $"<br><br>". $"<br>" would result in a new line with no space in between. | $"<br><br>"

(break)

(horizon)

[note: $<global> $<text> subnode]

The $<global> $<text> subnode contributes formatted DDTXT text to the document summary. There are no properties here. Original explanation: [href: ##chapter-6]. DDTXT Language: [href: ##chapter-7], [href: ##chapter-8], [href: ##chapter-9], [href: ##chapter-10], [href: ##chapter-11].

(divide)

[note: $<character> node]

The $<character> node has three types of $<subnodes>, $<style>, $<pronouns>, and $<text>. The main $<character> node itself has two properties. Original explanation: [href: ##chapter-4]

(break)
code #= single word | Word used to refer to this character in in-text references | NO DEFAULT; THIS IS MANDATORY
(break)
name #= Word(s) | How the reader sees characters in the finished, translated document | NO DEFAULT; THIS IS MANDATORY

(break)

(horizon)

[note: $<character> $<style> subnode]

Original explanation: [href: ##chapter-13].

(break)
color #= CSS color | Color of character's dialogue | "inherit" ("black")
(break)
paragraphColor #= CSS color | If specified, color of spoken words in dialogue, leaving only the name and colon to be the original color | Character color or "inherit" ("black")
(break)
backgroundColor #= CSS color | If specified, the color of the background behind the character's dialogue | None (document background color: "white")
(break)
dialoguePadding #= N%, where N is a number | The amount of padding (space between the dialogue and the text around it) to include. The amount should be no bigger than "2%". | "0%" or no padding

(break)

(horizon)

[note: $<character> $<pronouns> subnode]

This subnode sets the character's pronouns. Original explanation: [href: ##chapter-5]

(break)
subject #= word(s) | Subject pronoun | "they"
(break)
possessive #= word(s) | Possessive pronoun adjective | "their"
(break)
object #= word(s) | Direct and indirect object pronoun | "them"
(break)
reflexive #= word(s) | Reflexive pronoun | "themselves"
(break)
instance #= word(s) | What the character is an example or instance of | "person"
(break)
present #= word(s) | The subject pronoun combined with an "is" or "are" (for "they") | "they are"
(break)
presentCompacted #= word(s) | Contraction form of above | "they're"

(break)

(horizon)

[note: $<character> $<text> subnode]

The $<character> $<text> subnode contributes to the character's bio, which is shown in the document's summary box. There are no properties here. Original explanation: [href: ##chapter-6]. DDTXT Language: [href: ##chapter-7], [href: ##chapter-8], [href: ##chapter-9], [href: ##chapter-10], [href: ##chapter-11].

(divide)

[note: $<chapter> node]

The $<chapter> node has one type of subnode: the $<text> subnode. The main $<chapter> node itself has two properties. Both of these properties can be formatted with character references: [href: ##chapter-12].

(break)
name #= Name of chapter (DDTXT formatted) | This name appears in the bigger of the two headers and in the table of contents, when turned on. | "Untitled Chapter"
(break)
subtitle #= Subtitle of chapter (DDTXT formatted) | This subtitle appears in the smaller of the two headers, below the main chapter name. This subtitle does not appear in the table of contents. | "none" (no subtitle)

(break)

(horizon)

[note: $<chapter> $<text> subnode.]

The $<chapter> $<text> subnode contributes to the chapter's text, which is directly placed in your document. The chapters are placed in your document by order of placement in the raw DDTXT file. There are no properties here. Original explanation: [href: ##chapter-6]. DDTXT Language: [href: ##chapter-7], [href: ##chapter-8], [href: ##chapter-9], [href: ##chapter-10], [href: ##chapter-11].

</text>

</chapter>

