<chapter>

name = Current Limits of the DDTXT
subtitle = (and working around them)

<text>

The biggest problem with the DDTXT is poor localization and usefulness to languages other than English. For example, in Spanish, the DDTXT currently does not have anyway to change adjectives describing characters, which means that documents will break easily unless clever usage is applied.

(horizon)

// Accentos: , , , , , 

Por ejemplo, cuando se escribe DDTXTs en espaol, el languaje DDTXT no puede cambiar los adjetivos personales. Por eso, los documentos DDTXT les rompen fcilmente.

(break)

Una solucin es poner las referencias posesivas inmediatamente dentro de los adjetivos porque el languaje DDTXT puede leer las referencias dentro de estas palabras:

[text: "#@ejemplo es aburrid#=example." $--> "#@ejemplo es aburrid#="]

[translated: @ejemplo6 es aburrid=ejemplo6.]

[translated: @ejemplo7 es aburrid=ejemplo7.]

Para poner referencias posesivas dentro de las palabras, se necesita hacer el pronombre posesivo solamenta una letra (o, a, etc...). No s que esta accion sea dura, pero es mejor que nada.

(horizon)

Hopefully authors will be able to come up with ways to apply DDTXT references and tools to other languages, but I recognize that there will likely be problems using tools originally made for English. Other than this, the DDTXT language currently has some mostly minor problems.

(break)

For example, you may occasionally find that a character reference's translation is in lowercase when it really shouldn't be. This is due to guesswork as to what the start of a sentence really is. There are lots of scenarios that informally call for a new "sentence", grammatically correct or not. (Sometimes you want to write phrases independently or split sentences in different ways.) However, this is difficult to gauge, so at some point you may run across something like this.

[text: #@example1 ran out of groceries. (#<example1 went to the store.)]

[translated: @example1 ran out of groceries. (<example1 went to the store.)]

Even though the text in parentheses is a new sentence, the second reference is not capitalized because parentheses are often used for information inside of sentences. This example combines these two sentences to get rid of this problem.

[translated: @example1 ran out of groceries (so < went to the store).]

However, let's say that you really want to emphasize this passage as two separate sentences. If you have to you can add a word before the reference. This will make both sentences complete.

[translated: @ ran out of groceries. (So, < went to the store).]

As we write with this language more, we'll discover more issues to fix or work around, which means that there will most likely be more added as time passes.

</text>

</chapter>

